Since the circle is symmetric about the line $e = c$, the sum $e + c$ takes on all values between the minimum and maximum values of $e + c$ along the circle.

The minimum value of $e + c$ occurs when $e$ and $c$ are both as small as possible, which occurs when $(e,c)$ is the point on the circle closest to the origin.  This point is $(2 - 2 \sqrt{2},2 - 2 \sqrt{2})$, so the minimum value of $e + c$ is $2 \cdot (2 - 2 \sqrt{2}) = 4 - 4 \sqrt{2}$.

The maximum value of $e + c$ occurs when $e$ and $c$ are both as large as possible, which occurs when $(e,c)$ is the point on the circle farthest from the origin.  This point is $(2 + 2 \sqrt{2},2 + 2 \sqrt{2})$, so the maximum value of $e + c$ is $2 \cdot (2 + 2 \sqrt{2}) = 4 + 4 \sqrt{2}$.

Therefore, the sum of the constant terms can be any value between $4 - 4 \sqrt{2}$ and $4 + 4 \sqrt{2}$.

